162. Stem Cells. 1997;15 Suppl 2:59-67. doi: 10.1002/stem.5530150710.

Oxidative stress, signal transduction, and intercellular communication in 
radiation carcinogenesis.

Trosko JE(1), Inoue T.

Author information:
(1)Department of Pediatrics and Human Development, College of Human Medicine, 
Michigan State University, East Lansing, USA.

During the evolution of multicellular organisms, survival in an aerobic 
environment came about by adaptive responses, both to the endogenous oxidative 
metabolism within the cells of the organism as well as the chemicals and 
low-level radiation to which they are exposed. In addition to defense mechanisms 
shared with single-cell organisms, multicellular organisms are equipped with gap 
junctions which allow electrotonic and/or metabolic synchronization of processes 
between coupled cells. The connexin genes, which code for the proteins 
comprising the gap junctions, provide homeostatic regulation of cell 
proliferation, differentiation, and adaptive responses of individual cells 
through a mechanism of "gap junctional intercellular communication." The 
biological consequences of the response of a multicellular organism to low-level 
radiation exceeding the background level of oxidative damage to a cell in a 
tissue could be apoptosis, cell proliferation, or cell differentiation.

