176. J Fla Med Assoc. 1997 Aug-Sep;84(6):358-63.

Women's health care for the coming millennium.

Foster HW Jr(1).

Author information:
(1)Meharry Medical College, Nashville, Tennessee, USA.

In examining ways to improve female health care access and utilization, the 
magnitude of health problems must be examined before the design of solutions. 
Two types of barriers interfere with health care: attitudinal barriers blocking 
motivation to seek health care services and organizational barriers which block 
actual use of needed services. The major health problems of women in the United 
States are heart disease, cancer, stroke, lung-related diseases, intentional 
injuries, diabetes and HIV/AIDS. Public health has had a greater impact than 
high technology on the health of our nation. Balancing health care reform, 
changes in legislation and funding for medical education should help the United 
States be responsive to the challenge to move from substandard health for many 
women to superlative health care for all women and their family members.

